Author Scott Ellsworth provides just that in Midnight on the Potomac: The Last Year of the […]
title: Review of ‘Midnight on the Potomac’ by Scott Ellsworth

author: Rob Long
description: Part of being a student — even an old one, like me — is spending time in the library. As I write this, I am sitting in the Firestone Library at Princeton University, looking up at a wall festooned with names of honored, illustrious alumni and super-rich donors, two categories that do not always, or […]
title: Name change

author: Michael Taube
description: Godzilla has terrorized the Land of the Rising Sun for decades. Known as a kaiju (monster) in Japan, and King of the Monsters in the United States, Godzilla’s fearsome roar and atomic breath is a child’s nightmare come to life. It’s fought with and against other gigantic creatures. It’s struck fear in the hearts of […]
title: Godzilla then and now

author: W. James Antle III
description: Charlie Kirk loved to argue with liberals. That was apparent to all as he sought them out in national college tours. And if you attended any of his events or followed his viral social media posts, many liberals loved arguing with Kirk. College students, in particular, would line up to challenge Kirk’s views. He often […]
title: Charlie Kirk, 1993-2025

author: Nic Rowan
description: Until it closed last year, Monarch Novelties was the only souvenir store in Washington, D.C., that sold campaign memorabilia exclusive to the three presidential elections of the 1960s. The store was an oddity, a decaying building on 14th Street that, for more than 80 years, trafficked in eccentricities: not just Kennedy– and Nixon-era nostalgia but […]
title: Knickknack diaspora

author: Trent Reedy
description: Recently, Secretary of War Pete Hegseth has argued that during the Biden years, Army basic training became too soft and lost some of its hardcore edge. He wants basic training to toughen up. Which brings us to a phenomenon in the Army I’ll call the Hardcore Paradox: Soldiers enjoy comfort and dislike pain, stress, and […]
title: The hardcore paradox

author: Malcolm Forbes
description: Arundhati Roy dedicated her debut novel, The God of Small Things, to two people who, it was safe to assume, were her nearest and dearest: “For Mary Roy who grew me up,” she wrote, “Who loved me enough to let me go.” The other dedicatee was more cryptically designated: “For LKC, who, like me, survived.”  […]
title: Review of ‘Mother Mary Comes to Me’ by Arundhati Roy

author: Michael M. Rosen
description: “Nobody wants this!” Oscar Martinez of The Office insists to the documentary camera crew on the hunt for what became of the Dunder-Mifflin crew 12 years after the long-running program went off the air. “Don’t you guys have enough after nine years?” Evidently, no, Oscar. We need more. Much more. The Paper, which began streaming […]
title: Papering over ‘The Office’

author: Jessica Melugin
description: After a five-year legal battle that originated during the waning weeks of President Donald Trump‘s first administration, U.S. District Judge Amit P. Mehta recently ruled that Google illegally maintained a monopoly in search. Yet, Mehta said he would not force the divestiture of the search giant’s Chrome browser or Android operating system. Instead, the court banned exclusive […]
title: Judge’s Google antitrust ruling singes but doesn’t burn search giant

author: Ross O'Keefe
description: President Donald Trump said a Russian drone incursion into Poland that occurred during an attack on Ukraine earlier this week could have been an accident. European leaders have accused Russia of sending drones into Polish airspace to test the NATO alliance’s readiness. “Could’ve been a mistake. Could’ve been a mistake, but regardless, I’m not happy […]
title: Trump says Russian drone incursion into Poland ‘could’ve been a mistake’

author: Ross O'Keefe
description: The Utah college student who spoke with Charlie Kirk in the moments before his death spoke out Thursday, lamenting his death as a “tragedy.” Hunter Kozak had been speaking with Kirk about mass shootings when an assassin shot and killed Kirk right in front of him. Many pointed out the odd nature of the conversation […]
title: Student who asked Charlie Kirk final question stunned by his death: ‘It’s a tragedy’

author: Ross O'Keefe
description: President Donald Trump received an ovation from New York Yankees fans as he attended a game on the 24th anniversary of the 9/11 terrorist attacks. Trump saluted as the crowd cheered him. The Yankees played an integral part in the remembrance of 9/11. During the first game of the 2001 World Series, which was played […]
title: Trump gets ovation from Yankees fans after meeting with players on 9/11 anniversary

author: Ross O'Keefe
description: President Donald Trump has approved Wisconsin’s funding request, granting the state about $30 million in funds for flood recovery. The president, like in other approved funding requests, lauded his victories in the state. “I just informed Senator Ron Johnson that, based on his request, I am approving $29.8 Million Dollars for the wonderful State of […]
title: Trump grants funding request for Wisconsin floods, citing electoral victories in state

author: Ross O'Keefe
description: FBI Director Kash Patel will give an update on the manhunt for Charlie Kirk’s shooter at Utah Valley University on Thursday evening at 9:30 p.m. ET. FOREIGN LEADERS REMEMBER CHARLIE KIRK AS DEFENDER OF FREEDOM AFTER ACTIVIST’S ASSASSINATION Patel is expected to talk about the progress the bureau has made in pursuing Kirk’s killer. His […]
title: WATCH LIVE: Patel gives update on Charlie Kirk shooting as manhunt for gunman continues

author: Ross O'Keefe
description: The Utah Department of Public Safety released new photos of a person of interest in the Charlie Kirk shooting. The four new photos show a man in dark clothing and dark hair with a black backpack and gray-and-white shoes. He appears to have an American flag shirt on and is climbing a staircase in the […]
title: Utah DPS releases new photos of person of interest in Charlie Kirk shooting

author: Ross O'Keefe
description: Former Brazilian President Jair Bolsonaro has been sentenced to 27 years and three months in prison for his alleged 2022 coup attempt following the country’s presidential election. A panel of Brazilian Supreme Court justices handed down Bolsonaro’s sentence after convicting him of the attempted coup. Four of the five justices found Bolsonaro guilty on five […]
title: Former Brazilian President Bolsonaro sentenced to over 27 years in prison for coup attempt
